This is a tough game to write a review for. It's a surprisingly fun game with an absolutely terrible interface. When there is a list of items you have to very carefully touch the scroll bar and drag instead of scrolling like a normal touch screen application does. The buttons are very finicky and have to be pressed just the right length of time. Sometimes when unselecting a character and pressing elsewhere on the screen, the previously selected character is chosen. It's hard to tell when any item is selected as there is inconsistent use of highlighting when a widget is touched. Tabs cannot be swiped in between, they have to very carefully be touched.  I am guessing that this is a straight port of a flash game and it demonstrates why lazy programming is so bad. And yet, the game is surprisingly fun and I have spent several hours of time playing it already.

The game has a cursor in the middle of the screen that can take precedence over taps and swipes; for instance, it could grab the current dungeon in progress and interpret all taps as you tapping on the dungeon.  I also noticed that the game is scaled to tablet size, including the size of the taps. Yes, the game uses regions of the touchscreen to detect taps and swipes, not Android's built-in handlers!

The game is loads of fun with many interesting options, but there is a definite endpoint where there is suddenly nothing left to do. Congratulations you won. Now restart. The endgame is not very well balanced though - expect to either be crushed utterly or to plow through the game with no challenge, depending on how well you built your town and trained your heroes up to that point. The first playthrough is mostly a learning experience; the second is the one where you win.

I've played many, but not all, Kairosoft games and this one is in my top two (with Game Dev Story).  In this game you're not directly controlling the adventurers, but instead play the role of the town mayor which builds and organizes the town resources to enable adventurers to go out and... well.... adventure.  You can direct them to some extent by sending them on quests to explore dungeons and kill monster hordes but that is about it.  Some really awesome creativity in the naming of the characters and the various building attributes etc make it very fun.  I highly recommend this as a starting point for Kairosoft games.  For my full video review checkout my YouTube channel:  PixelFreakGames

Biggest issue: Need internet connection to play.  That means I cannot play this game while on a plane or traveling in subway (no phone signal) or if roaming.  It is for the internet limitation that I rate it 3.  If I pay for a game, I expect to be able to play it anywhere.

A stunning, exceptionally entertaining clone of those wonderful final fantasy/ultima games for the Game Boy, GBA and Palm devices from the late 90's early 2000s.  If you liked those older games, you'll love this one.  This is a true standalone game without so much of a hint of in-app purchases, ads, or upselling.    I am pleased by the variables and multitude of upgrade elements in the game.  You wouldn't think a FF clone like this would be so enjoyable and playable for hours upon end, but it is.  It can be quite challenging, too.  You also wouldn't think a game like this, which is just a very well made clone of decade old games, would drain your battery faster than any other app or game you have and turn it into a hotplate, but it does.  This game blasts through battery faster than 3D Shooters or half gig or whole gig games like Batman or Broken Sword.  For that weirdness, I must deduct a star.

The game is fun and addictive but I can't feel like the developer is trying.  I skipped I do not know how many variations but the kairosoft games I have played are  -Game Dev Story -and This.  There is not much variations in how you can build your adventurers, nor can you select who you want to do dungeon for you. Did the developer even bother playing the game himself to see what is wrong with the formula? In addition, I never find myself settling down and watching my adventurers play the game for me and I am always busy building stuff and making events. Even Game Dev Story had mini pauses to let your hands have a rest, but not this game. You are constantly poking away, gifting you townsmen, trying to make them happy, hold events to earn satisfaction points, building houses for the adventurers, upgrading the shops.   TL:DR: You seem to have made everyone satisfied kairosoft, everyone except the actual player.

More fun but less challenging than Game Dev Story, Dungeon Village does an excellent job of giving players their very own virtual RPG town.  Build, manage and evolve every part of the town from the decorations to its tenants.  For those complaining about automated battles and not enough customization for your heroes: - This game revolves around growing your village. - By building certain structures and growing certain industries through appeal you boost specific hero stats. - The game has at least 10 different unlockable hero classes and twice as many weapons, armors, spells, buildings and other items, allowing players to make teams of everything from wrestlers, clowns and ninjas to knights, bards and magicians, each with uniquely customized stats, abilities and inventories.   For everyone having issues with making shops successful: - Use items on buildings to improve their stats - Appeal makes heroes visit more often - Quality, I think, raises the effectiveness of the stat boosts - Price increases how much adventurers spend each visit  *Spoiler - last classes: King, Princess, Kairobot  Overall a very well executed game with a ton content and customization, and simple interface.

I have enjoyed all the previous Kairosoft games that they have offered, this one seems to be a collection of the ideas. While the game seems to be a great idea, the implementation seems to be a few of each of the ideas but not strongly. Each aspect, town maintenance/building maintenance (Mega Mall Story, Epic Astro Story, Hot Springs Story etc...), character development (Pocket League Story, Game Dev Story, Epic Astro Story, etc...) and monster combat (Epic Astro Story) seem to all be done in small-ish pieces of the puzzle to make a composite game. While this seemingly should work, its ends up being so little from each that the game loses focus and excitement. I would be happier if it let me hire the heroes. If I will be arming them and such, Let me have complete control of them. If they are a wizard, I want the toon to stand back and cast not attack with a sword. With added character control and less looped music the game would be higher on my list. Right now, I would say, try the lite version, it may not be for you.

Ran great on my Galaxy S2 and didn't seem to drain my battery as much as their other games. I have to agree with the other reviews here though, the replay value isn't that great. On my 2nd playthrough I managed to get a 5 stars town (the goal of the game) by the 5th year (out of 15) and while there's still some fun to be had, I feel like I've already seen everything the game has to offer. It's still worth a five stars review though as the game is better than 99.9% of what's available on the app store.
